<paragraph id="8B905B69B600FF8AFEE3FF29FDC1FF23" blockId="7.[358,583,194,218]" box="[358,583,194,218]" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">
<heading id="D0D8EC05B600FF8AFEE3FF29FDC1FF23" box="[358,583,194,218]" centered="true" fontSize="9" level="2" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" reason="2">
THE 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB600FF8AFE1AFF2DFDC1FF23" authority="ISSUE" box="[415,583,198,217]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Danaus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="erippus">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFE1AFF2DFE78FF23" box="[415,510,198,217]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">ERIPPUS</emphasis>
ISSUE
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B905B69B600FF8AFF27FEEAFEA5FD7C" blockId="7.[162,779,257,1904]" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">
From its first description as 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB600FF8AFE70FEEAFF5DFECF" authority="Cramer, 1775" authorityName="Cramer" authorityYear="1775" class="Insecta" family="Papilionidae" genus="Papilio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="erippus">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFE70FEEAFD25FEED" box="[501,675,257,279]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">Papilio erippus</emphasis>
Cramer, 1775
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB600FF8AFF63FECBFEBCFECF" authorityName="Cramer" authorityYear="1775" box="[230,314,288,309]" class="Insecta" family="Papilionidae" genus="Papilio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="erippus">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFF63FECBFEBCFECF" box="[230,314,288,309]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">erippus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been conventionally separated from 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB600FF8AFF27FED5FE88FEA9" baseAuthorityName="LINNAEUS" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[162,270,318,339]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Danaus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="plexippus">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFF27FED5FE88FEA9" box="[162,270,318,339]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">plexippus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which it replaces south of the Amazon. However, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFBE2698B600FF8AFE93FEB6FE31FE89" author="Forbes WTM" box="[278,439,349,371]" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" pagination="101 - 140" refId="ref15693" refString="Forbes WTM. 1939. Revisional notes on the Danainae. Entomologica Americana 19: 101 - 140." type="journal article" year="1939">Forbes (1939)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFBE2698B600FF8AFE42FEB6FDDDFE89" author="Clark AH" box="[455,603,349,371]" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" pagination="531 - 542" refId="ref15327" refString="Clark AH. 1941. Notes on some North and Middle American danaid butterflies. Proceedings of the United States National Museum 1941: 531 - 542." type="journal article" year="1941">Clark (1941)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="EFBE2698B600FF8AFD18FEB6FEA7FE68" author="Urquhart FA" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" refId="ref17543" refString="Urquhart FA. 1960. The monarch butterfly. Toronto: Toronto University Press." type="book" year="1960">Urquhart (1960: 179)</bibRefCitation>
treated 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB600FF8AFE06FE97FE51FE6B" authorityName="Cramer" authorityYear="1775" box="[387,471,380,401]" class="Insecta" family="Papilionidae" genus="Papilio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="erippus">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFE06FE97FE51FE6B" box="[387,471,380,401]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">erippus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as one of three subspecies of 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB600FF8AFF4CFE71FEB3FE55" baseAuthorityName="LINNAEUS" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[201,309,410,431]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Danaus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="plexippus">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFF4CFE71FEB3FE55" box="[201,309,410,431]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">plexippus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(the other two being the migratory 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB600FF8AFF27FE52FE88FE34" baseAuthorityName="LINNAEUS" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[162,270,441,462]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Danaus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" sensu="stricto" species="plexippus">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFF27FE52FE88FE34" box="[162,270,441,462]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">plexippus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A2683A00B600FF8AFE9FFE51FEBAFE34" box="[282,316,441,463]" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" sensu="stricto">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFE9FFE51FEB0FE35" box="[282,310,442,463]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">s.s</emphasis>
.
</taxonomicNameLabel>
and the nonmigratory 
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFDDCFE52FD4BFE34" box="[601,717,441,462]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">megalippe</emphasis>
). On the other hand, by the time he reached p. 182, Urquhart had changed his mind and 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB600FF8AFDA6FE1CFD10FDF6" authorityName="Cramer" authorityYear="1775" box="[547,662,503,524]" class="Insecta" family="Papilionidae" genus="Papilio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="erippus">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFDA6FE1CFD10FDF6" box="[547,662,503,524]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">D. erippus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was once more a species! Whereas A &amp; V-W grudgingly award 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB600FF8AFF27FDDFFF70FDB3" authorityName="Cramer" authorityYear="1775" box="[162,246,564,585]" class="Insecta" family="Papilionidae" genus="Papilio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="erippus">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFF27FDDFFF70FDB3" box="[162,246,564,585]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">erippus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
specific status, they say it is ‘hardly distinct’ and ‘may be better regarded as conspecific [with 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB600FF8AFF27FD9AFE88FD7C" baseAuthorityName="LINNAEUS" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[162,270,625,646]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Danaus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="plexippus">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFF27FD9AFE88FD7C" box="[162,270,625,646]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">plexippus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
]’.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C33508E2B600FF8AFF3EFD7BFDE1FB88" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" type="description">
<paragraph id="8B905B69B600FF8AFF3EFD7BFDE1FB88" blockId="7.[162,779,257,1904]" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">
The only distinguishing character observed in adult butterflies is the paler hindwing margin of 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB600FF8AFD30FD44FC8FFD3E" authorityName="Cramer" authorityYear="1775" box="[693,777,687,708]" class="Insecta" family="Papilionidae" genus="Papilio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="erippus">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFD30FD44FC8FFD3E" box="[693,777,687,708]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">erippus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
compared to 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB600FF8AFEB9FD26FE2EFD18" baseAuthorityName="LINNAEUS" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[316,424,717,738]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Danaus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="plexippus">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFEB9FD26FE2EFD18" box="[316,424,717,738]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">plexippus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFE6CFD26FDDBFD18" box="[489,605,717,738]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">megalippe</emphasis>
(character 60, Appendix 1A). However, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFBE2698B600FF8AFE4BFD07FD03FCFB" author="Kitching IJ" box="[462,645,747,770]" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" pagination="1 - 97" refId="ref15993" refString="Kitching IJ. 1985. Early stages and the classification of the milkweed butterflies (Lepidoptera: Danainae). Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society 85: 1 - 97." type="journal article" year="1985">Kitching (1985)</bibRefCitation>
found two pupal characters to distinguish 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB600FF8AFD8DFCE0FDDAFCDA" authorityName="Cramer" authorityYear="1775" box="[520,604,779,800]" class="Insecta" family="Papilionidae" genus="Papilio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="erippus">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFD8DFCE0FDDAFCDA" box="[520,604,779,800]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">erippus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB600FF8AFD1BFCE1FC8CFCE5" baseAuthorityName="LINNAEUS" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[670,778,778,799]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Danaus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="plexippus">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFD1BFCE1FC8CFCE5" box="[670,778,778,799]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">plexippus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and subsequently (
<bibRefCitation id="EFBE2698B600FF8AFE0FFCC2FDBDFCC5" author="Kitching IJ" box="[394,571,809,831]" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" pagination="367 - 389" refId="ref16025" refString="Kitching IJ. 1986. Allozyme variation in the milkweed butterflies (Lepidoptera: Danainae). Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society 86: 367 - 389." type="journal article" year="1986">Kitching, 1986</bibRefCitation>
) identified three diagnostic allozyme differences, though his sample of 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB600FF8AFF27FC8CFF70FC86" authorityName="Cramer" authorityYear="1775" box="[162,246,871,892]" class="Insecta" family="Papilionidae" genus="Papilio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="erippus">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFF27FC8CFF70FC86" box="[162,246,871,892]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">erippus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was small (
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFE09FC8CFE26FC86" box="[396,416,871,892]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">N</emphasis>
= 9, plus 9 progeny). We have sequenced the mitochondrial 12S (344 bp) and nuclear 18S rRNA (525 bp) genes of both 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB600FF8AFDA1FC4FFD16FC43" baseAuthorityName="LINNAEUS" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[548,656,932,953]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Danaus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="plexippus">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFDA1FC4FFD16FC43" box="[548,656,932,953]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">plexippus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry id="F3381BF9B600FF8AFD50FC4FFF64FC22" name="Australia" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">Australia</collectingCountry>
(
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFF71FC28FE8EFC22" box="[244,264,963,984]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">N</emphasis>
= 8) and north-eastern America (
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFD15FC28FD22FC22" box="[656,676,963,984]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">N</emphasis>
= 4) and 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB600FF8AFF27FC09FF70FC0D" authorityName="Cramer" authorityYear="1775" box="[162,246,994,1015]" class="Insecta" family="Papilionidae" genus="Papilio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="erippus">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFF27FC09FF70FC0D" box="[162,246,994,1015]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">erippus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFE8BFC09FEA4FC0D" box="[270,290,994,1015]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">N</emphasis>
= 1) and found no differences. Whereas both these genes are relatively conserved, the 12S locus is, nevertheless, otherwise 100% diagnostic for all the 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB600FF8AFF7DFBD5FE2BFBA9" box="[248,429,1085,1107]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Danaus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFF7DFBD5FED7FBA9" box="[248,337,1086,1107]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">Danaus</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
, and even some subspecies of 
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFF27FBB7FEE5FB8B" box="[162,355,1116,1137]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB600FF8AFF27FBB7FEBDFB8B" authorityName="Smith &amp; Lushai &amp; Allen" authorityYear="2005" baseAuthorityName="LINNAEUS" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[162,315,1116,1137]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Danaus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chrysippus">D. chrysippus</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A2683A00B600FF8AFEC1FBB7FEE5FB8B" box="[324,355,1116,1137]" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" sensu="lato">s.l.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFBE2698B600FF8AFEF1FBB7FDDDFB88" author="Lushai G &amp; Smith DAS &amp; Gordon IJ &amp; Goulson D &amp; Allen JA &amp; Maclean N" box="[372,603,1116,1138]" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" pagination="236 - 246" refId="ref16222" refString="Lushai G, Smith DAS, Gordon IJ, Goulson D, Allen JA, Maclean N. 2003 a. Incomplete sexual isolation in sympatry between subspecies of the butterfly Danaus chrysippus (L.) and the creation of a hybrid zone. Heredity 90: 236 - 246." type="journal article" year="2003">
Lushai 
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFE49FBB7FE7BFB8B" box="[460,509,1116,1137]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">et al</emphasis>
., 2003a
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C33508E2B600FF8AFF3EFB91FA0BFEAE" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="8B905B69B600FF8AFF3EFB91FE80F9FA" blockId="7.[162,779,257,1904]" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">
The 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB600FF8AFF7FFB90FE1DFB6A" authority="issue" box="[250,411,1146,1168]" class="Insecta" family="Papilionidae" genus="Papilio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="erippus">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFF7FFB90FEC8FB6A" box="[250,334,1147,1168]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">erippus</emphasis>
issue
</taxonomicName>
has, however, recently been addressed by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFBE2698B600FF8AFED6FB72FD34FB55" author="Brower AVZ &amp; Jeansonne MM" box="[339,690,1177,1199]" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" pagination="519 - 523" refId="ref15107" refString="Brower AVZ, Jeansonne MM. 2004. Geographical populations and ' subspecies' of New World monarch butterflies (Danaus plexippus (L.) Nymphalidae) share a recent origin and are not phylogenetically distinct. Annals of the Entomological Society of America 97: 519 - 523." type="journal article" year="2004">Brower &amp; Jeansonne (2004)</bibRefCitation>
. Using mtDNA sequence data from the COI, 
<subScript id="17AB592CB600FF8AFDFFFB53FD57FB35" attach="left" box="[634,721,1208,1231]" fontSize="6" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">tRNAleu</subScript>
and COII loci, they find an average genetic divergence (GD) of 4.8% between 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB600FF8AFE1EFB1DFE69FAF1" box="[411,495,1270,1291]" class="Insecta" family="Papilionidae" genus="Papilio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="erippus">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFE1EFB1DFE69FAF1" box="[411,495,1270,1291]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">erippus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(represented by only 
<specimenCount id="9D2990E0B600FF8AFD64FB1EFE8BFAD0" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" type="generic">one specimen</specimenCount>
) and 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB600FF8AFED6FAFFFE39FAD3" baseAuthorityName="LINNAEUS" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[339,447,1300,1321]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Danaus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="plexippus">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFED6FAFFFE39FAD3" box="[339,447,1300,1321]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">plexippus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
+ 
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFE65FAFFFDD2FAD3" box="[480,596,1300,1321]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">megalippe</emphasis>
, compared to a pairwise mean GD of only 0.3% that separates geographically diverse samples among the latter group. Thus, they claim that 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB600FF8AFE20FA9BFD9EFA7F" box="[421,536,1392,1413]" class="Insecta" family="Papilionidae" genus="Papilio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="erippus">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFE20FA9BFD9EFA7F" box="[421,536,1392,1413]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">D. erippus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a distinct species, as originally described by Cramer, and not merely a southern race of 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB600FF8AFEEDFA45FE75FA38" baseAuthorityName="LINNAEUS" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[360,499,1453,1475]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Danaus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="plexippus">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFEEDFA45FE75FA38" box="[360,499,1453,1475]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">D. plexippus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, as suggested by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFBE2698B600FF8AFD46FA46FDA7FA18" author="Kitching IJ &amp; Ackery PR &amp; Vane-Wright RI" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" pagination="11 - 16" refId="ref16054" refString="Kitching IJ, Ackery PR, Vane-Wright RI. 1993. Systematic perspectives on the evolution of the monarch butterfly. In: Malcolm SB, Zalucki MP, eds. Biology and conservation of the monarch butterfly. Los Angeles, CA: Los Angeles County Museum of Natural History, 11 - 16." type="book chapter" year="1993">Kitching, Ackery &amp; Vane-Wright (1993)</bibRefCitation>
. We concur with this decision.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B905B69B600FF8AFF3EF9E2FA0BFEAE" blockId="7.[162,779,257,1904]" lastBlockId="7.[826,1442,196,340]" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">
Applying the 1.2% per million years mtDNA divergence rate hypothesized for closely related insect taxa (
<bibRefCitation id="EFBE2698B600FF8AFF2CF9ADFEC8F9A6" author="Brower AVZ" box="[169,334,1606,1628]" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" pagination="6491 - 6495" refId="ref15066" refString="Brower AVZ. 1994. Rapid morphological radiation and convergence among races of the butterfly. Heliconius erato inferred from patterns of mitochondrial DNA evolution. Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences, USA 91: 6491 - 6495." type="journal article" year="1994">Brower, 1994</bibRefCitation>
), the separation of 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB600FF8AFDDCF9ACFD4DF9A6" box="[601,715,1607,1628]" class="Insecta" family="Papilionidae" genus="Papilio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="erippus">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFDDCF9ACFD4DF9A6" box="[601,715,1607,1628]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">D. erippus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB600FF8AFF27F98DFEABF980" baseAuthorityName="LINNAEUS" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[162,301,1637,1659]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Danaus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="plexippus">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFF27F98DFEABF980" box="[162,301,1637,1659]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">D. plexippus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
probably occurred some 2 million years ago (late Pliocene-early Pleistocene). We suggest the possibility that an ancestral 
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFE73F949FD39F94D" box="[502,703,1698,1719]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">erippus-plexippus</emphasis>
population was initially divided during an interglacial period around this time, when successive raised sealevels of + 
<quantity id="4CD7F68CB600FF8AFE92F915FEDBF8EE" box="[279,349,1790,1812]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" unit="m" value="100.0">100 m</quantity>
and + 
<quantity id="4CD7F68CB600FF8AFE22F915FE59F8EE" box="[423,479,1790,1812]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" unit="m" value="60.0">60 m</quantity>
(compared to the present day) occurred. At such times Amazonia was inundated and became a series of huge brackish and freshwater lakes that extended west from the Atlantic to the foot of the Andes in eastern 
<collectingCountry id="F3381BF9B600FF8AFBCBFF2FFB03FF23" box="[1102,1157,196,217]" name="Peru" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">Peru</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFBE2698B600FF8AFB11FF2FFAA3FF20" author="Haffer J" box="[1172,1317,196,218]" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" pagination="1 - 18" refId="ref15761" refString="Haffer J. 1987. Quaternary history of tropical America. In: Whitmore TC, Prance GT, eds. Biogeography and quaternary history in tropical America. Oxford: Clarendon Press, 1 - 18." type="book chapter" year="1987">Haffer, 1987</bibRefCitation>
). A succession of Amazon embayments formed a geographical barrier that could have isolated 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB600FF8AFB33FEE9FA8CFEED" box="[1206,1290,258,279]" class="Insecta" family="Papilionidae" genus="Papilio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="erippus">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFB33FEE9FA8CFEED" box="[1206,1290,258,279]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">erippus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to the south from 
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFCFBFECBFC74FECF" box="[894,1010,288,309]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">megalippe</emphasis>
to the north for several thousand years at a stretch, ample time to trigger speciation.
</paragraph>
